    description = 'A landmark inter-denominational biographical work by the Maliki jurist Ali ibn Muhammad ibn Ahmad al-Makki (Ibn al-Sabbagh, d. 855 AH/1451 CE) that presents comprehensive biographies of the Twelve Imams of Shia Islam. This unique work bridges Sunni and Shia scholarship by synthesizing Shia biographical sources (primarily al-Irbili''s Kashf al-Ghumma) with respected Sunni hadith collections including Sahih al-Bukhari, Sahih Muslim, and Ahmad ibn Hanbal''s Musnad. Organized into twelve chapters, each devoted to one Imam, the work provides detailed treatment of Imam Ali, Imam al-Husayn, and Imam al-Mahdi while maintaining scholarly objectivity and diplomatic presentation. Ibn al-Sabbagh''s methodological approach avoids sectarian polemics while demonstrating reverence for Imamic tradition, creating a rare example of successful cross-sectarian Islamic scholarship that has served both Sunni and Shia communities for over seven centuries. The work represents an important contribution to Islamic biographical literature and inter-denominational understanding.'
